105. The usual construction with opus est is impersonal, the thing needed being in the ablative and the person needing it in the dative:— “

Libris mihi opus est, I need books.

But when the thing needed is expressed by a neuter pronoun or adjective the personal construction must be used:—

Multa nobis opus sunt, we need many things (lit. many things are necessary ‚to us). ’ ”’

Note that opus and fisus are never declined in this construction. Usus is much rarer than opus.
